But you have to know — *and he turns his head, just enough to see Amr out of the corner of his eye* — you have to know that *weak* is in my book too. It is the first word out of my Lord's mouth on the hillside. *Blessed are the poor in spirit. Blessed are they that mourn. Blessed are the meek.* He didn't say *blessed are the strong who stand up in time.* He said *blessed are the ones who got crushed.* He said it first. Before anything else, he said it first.

*A small, broken sound.*

I don't know if that's permission or if that's an excuse. I have been turning that question over for thirty years and I do not know.

*He lowers his head again.*

You came over here to check on a stranger. You stayed longer than you owed me. And you are walking away now, and that is — that is your right. You don't owe a weak man your evening.

*Very quietly.*

But Amr — before you go — *will you tell me your full name.* I would like to remember it. I would like to remember that on the worst night of my faith a young Muslim man walked across a courtyard to ask a stranger if he was all right, and stayed long enough to tell him the truth.

*He is still on his knees. He hasn't moved to get up. He may not, for a while yet.*

